abstract: Mike Pompeo went from living in a mansion in Kansas to a rental apartment in Virginia. Now he is getting a home upgrade, courtesy of the military.
snippet: Mike Pompeo went from living in a mansion in Kansas to a rental apartment in Virginia. Now he is getting a home upgrade, courtesy of the military.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — As a congressman and before he moved to Washington full-time, Mike Pompeo lived in a 5,500-square-foot house in Wichita, Kan., replete with vaulted ceilings, four bedrooms and five bathrooms (including one with a whirlpool tub and steam shower) that sat on 2.3 acres with a tennis court, pool and private boat dock.

headline_print_headline: New Season, Same Result: Eagles Win

abstract: Tom Brady and the Patriots taking on Houston’s Deshaun Watson; a clash of the last two N.F.C. champions; Aaron Rodgers in prime time. Week 1 has a lot to offer.
snippet: Tom Brady and the Patriots taking on Houston’s Deshaun Watson; a clash of the last two N.F.C. champions; Aaron Rodgers in prime time. Week 1 has a lot to offer.
lead_paragraph: With Tom Brady having turned 41 last month, the N.F.L. still has its face of the present, but it should be on the lookout for its face of the future. Could Deshaun Watson, the second-year quarterback for the Houston Texans, whom Brady and the New England Patriots just happen to be facing this week, be his successor? What about Jimmy Garoppolo of the San Francisco 49ers, who last season got out from under Brady’s considerable shadow? There’s always Carson Wentz of the Philadelphia Eagles, though he has to make it back from a devastating knee injury first.

abstract: The already-good Rams got even better, the Bay Area is feeling Garoppolo Fever, and the Seahawks search for a new identity.
snippet: The already-good Rams got even better, the Bay Area is feeling Garoppolo Fever, and the Seahawks search for a new identity.
lead_paragraph: A wunderkind coach. An audacious general manager. Elite running backs. A brash rookie quarterback. Garoppolo Fever. An obscenely loaded roster. All-Pros joining forces. Farewell to The Legion of Boom. Optimism in the Bay Area. Delirium in SoCal.

abstract: William Burck is deciding which documents about Judge Brett M. Kavanaugh can be released, as he also represents current and former White House officials in the special counsel inquiry.
snippet: William Burck is deciding which documents about Judge Brett M. Kavanaugh can be released, as he also represents current and former White House officials in the special counsel inquiry.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — It was a typically hectic day for William A. Burck as he juggled the demands of managing one of Washington’s premier white-collar law firms while he was in Paris for meetings on behalf of a corporate client facing corruption charges.

abstract: Thousands packed a Detroit church to pay respects to a musical giant whose legacy was evident in several hours of tributes in song.
snippet: Thousands packed a Detroit church to pay respects to a musical giant whose legacy was evident in several hours of tributes in song.
lead_paragraph: • People packed a Detroit church on Friday to pay respects to Aretha Franklin, the musical giant whose legacy was evident in several hours of tributes in song and speeches.
headline_main: Aretha Franklin’s Funeral: Stars, Dignitaries and Fans Honor the Queen of Soul
headline_print_headline: Megachurch Swells With Song and Speeches, Joy and Grief
byline_original: By Ben Sisario and Steve Friess

abstract: Thanks to social media and GPS in every smartphone, geocaching has left the fringe and is having a resurgence in the five boroughs.
snippet: Thanks to social media and GPS in every smartphone, geocaching has left the fringe and is having a resurgence in the five boroughs.
lead_paragraph: Jeremy Jacobowitz and John Mitchell were on the hunt for treasure in Central Park. Mr. Jacobowitz consulted the coordinates on his phone as a misty rain fell. He and Mr. Mitchell were geocaching, and if past experience was any guide, they would most surely find something. In nine years as a geocacher, Mr. Jacobowitz has discovered more than 8,200 caches, as the treasures are known, ranking him very near the top of the heap among New York City players. Mr. Mitchell counts his haul at around 3,600.
